=== Ranking of runners-up ===
On 14 March 2025, CAF notified its member associations that matches against sixth-place teams would be excluded when ranking the runners-up, due to Group E having five teams following the withdrawal of [[Eritrea national football team|Eritrea]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://x.com/windowintlpod/status/1976346552588435512 |title=The International Window on X |date=9 October 2025 |access-date=9 October 2025}}</ref> This information was not announced publicly by either CAF or FIFA.

{{2026 FIFA World Cup qualification - CAF group tables|Runners-up}}

==Second round==
{{main|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round}}

The four best group runners-up ([[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]], [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]], and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]) advanced to play-offs to determine the sole CAF representative at the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification#Inter-confederation play-offs|inter-confederation play-offs]]. The matchups for the semi-final were based on the 17 October 2025 [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA rankings]], with the highest-ranked side taking on the lowest and the second-highest taking on the third-highest.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/spain-top-argentina-second-world-ranking|title=Spain stay top as Argentina move back to second|work=FIFA|access-date=17 October 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gleeson |first1=Mark |title=Morocco to host African World Cup playoffs |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/morocco-host-african-world-cup-playoffs-2025-10-12/ |website=Reuters |date=12 October 2025 |access-date=12 October 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Elikplim |first1=Bokor |title=CAF confirms Morocco as host for 2026 World Cup African play-off tournament - AfricaSoccer.com |url=https://africasoccer.com/caf-confirms-morocco-as-host-for-2026-world-cup-african-play-off-tournament/ |access-date=12 October 2025 |date=12 October 2025}}</ref> A total of three matches were played, all hosted in Morocco.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kabbour |first1=Abderrahim |title=Morocco to Host African Playoff Matches for World Cup Qualifiers |url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2025/10/263215/morocco-to-host-african-playoff-matches-for-world-cup-qualifiers/ |website=Morocco World News |access-date=12 October 2025 |date=12 October 2025}}</ref>

{{#section:2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round|Summary}}

==Inter-confederation play-offs==
{{Main|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)}}

The winner of the second round, [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]], joined [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] (from [[CONMEBOL]]), [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] (from [[Asian Football Confederation|AFC]]), [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] and [[Suriname national football team|Suriname]] (both from [[CONCACAF]]), and [[New Caledonia national football team|New Caledonia]] (from [[Oceania Football Confederation|OFC]]) in the inter-confederation play-offs.

The teams were ranked according to the November 2025 [[FIFA Men's World Ranking]], with the four lowest-ranked teams playing in two {{nowrap|single-elimination}} matches. The winners met the two highest-ranked teams in another set of {{nowrap|single-elimination}} matches, with the winners of these matches qualifying for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/play-off-tournament-draw-results|title=Path to 2026 laid out for Play-Off Tournament hopefuls|date=20 November 2025|access-date=20 November 2025|publisher=FIFA}}</ref>

